<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-21T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-21T19:00:00-05:00" n="49" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d49">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 658.119/234a</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Minister in Sweden</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MIN1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Morris</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-21T19:00:00-05:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">February 21, 1918, 7 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>559. Formal announcement was made here on morning of February 20 of
                                relaxation of embargo against Sweden and Holland, giving articles,
                                exportation of which would be permitted. Prospective exporters were
                                instructed that their importer must first notify you of their
                                intention to import and then apply for export license from War Trade
                                Board, and that no British letters of assurance would be issued. The
                                comprehensive plan for the elimination of navicerts, a copy of which
                                you presumably have received from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName>, is thus
                                being put into effect. In accordance with that plan you will cable
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName>
                                of proposed imports and he will notify London Contraband Committee.
                                The War Trade Board, prior to issuing export licenses, will cable
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName>
                                for recommendation of Contraband Committee.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>